This question will resolve based on the release date of the specific recording that tops the charts. It is immaterial whether a different version of the single was recorded and released previously.&#x20;

For example in 2004, this question would have resolved as 2000s because that year's Christmas number one: Band Aid 20's version of "Do They Know It's Christmas?," was released in 2004, even though the original "Do They Know It's Christmas?" was recorded and released in 1984.

Each decade will be defined by the first three digits of the year. For example, any recording released between January 1, 1990, and December 31, 1999, will be considered a 1990s release.

question_details.description:
The first round of Chile's election was [held](https://americasquarterly.org/article/reaction-jara-and-kast-head-to-chiles-presidential-runoff/) on November 16, 2026. Jeannette Jara of the incumbent [Unidad por Chile](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unidad_por_Chile) electoral alliance which includes her party, the Communist Party of Chile, won 26.9% of the votes. Her opponent in the runoff, José Kast of the right wing [Change for Chile](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Change_for_Chile) alliance, won 23.9% of the vote. With no one winning a 50% of the vote, a runoff between Jara and Kast is scheduled for December 14, 2025.&#x20;

Kast and Jara represent radically different ideologies. Jara is the [first](https://www.tsgco.com/post/how-chiles-aunt-became-their-first-communist-presidential-candidate) communist to represent a broad political coalition (in this case left of center) and the first to win the first round. As labor minister under outgoing President Gabriel Boric, she oversaw an increase in Chile's minimum wage and a new law phasing in a 40-hour workweek.

José Kast is making his third run for president; in the[ 2021 election](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_Chilean_general_election) he lost to Boric by 12 points. In the years since then, Chile has seen a massive rise in [crime](https://www.rusi.org/explore-our-research/publications/commentary/criminality-taking-over-chile-and-politicians-cant-seem-fix-it) and [illegal immigration](https://mixedmigration.org/chiles-response-to-migration/). Kast has [praised](https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2025/11/04/world/politics/pinochet-crime-nostalgia-chile/) strongman Augusto Pinochet and vowed to [crack down](https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/nov/12/jose-antonio-kast-trump-inspired-frontrunner-chile-president) on crime and [deport](https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/latin-america/chile-presidential-candidate-proposes-action-against-illegal-immigration.phtml) illegal migrants, with those who have committed crimes being confined to a special prison.&#x20;

In the first round of the election, right-of-center candidates [won](https://www.ft.com/content/4d9abd84-b792-4b60-a59a-390192a8c8c5) 70% of the vote. Thus, according to the [Financial Times](https://www.ft.com/content/4d9abd84-b792-4b60-a59a-390192a8c8c5):

> Pollsters say it will be far easier for Kast than Jara to pick up the roughly 45 per cent of votes won by three other opposition candidates, giving him a clear advantage in the second round on December 14.

